Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

A sales forecast is a prediction of future sales revenue based on historical data, industry trends, and the status of the current sales pipeline. Businesses use the sales forecast to estimate weekly, monthly, quarterly, and annual sales totals. A company needs to make an accurate sales forecast as it adds value across an organization and helps the different verticals to chalk out their future course of action.

Forecasting helps an organization plan its sales operations by region and provides valuable insights to the supply chain team regarding the procurement of goods and materials. An accurate sales forecast process has many benefits which include improved decision-making about the future and reduction of sales pipeline and forecast risks. Moreover, it helps to reduce the time spent in planning territory coverage and establish benchmarks that can be used to assess trends in the future.

Objective¶

SuperKart is a retail chain operating supermarkets and food marts across various tier cities, offering a wide range of products. To optimize its inventory management and make informed decisions around regional sales strategies, SuperKart wants to accurately forecast the sales revenue of its outlets for the upcoming quarter.

To operationalize these insights at scale, the company has partnered with a data science firmnot just to build a predictive model based on historical sales data, but to develop and deploy a robust forecasting solution that can be integrated into SuperKarts decision-making systems and used across its network of stores.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of the various products and stores.The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • Product_Id - unique identifier of each product, each identifier having two letters at the beginning followed by a number.
  • Product_Weight - weight of each product
  • Product_Sugar_Content - sugar content of each product like low sugar, regular and no sugar
  • Product_Allocated_Area - ratio of the allocated display area of each product to the total display area of all the products in a store
  • Product_Type - broad category for each product like meat, snack foods, hard drinks, dairy, canned, soft drinks, health and hygiene, baking goods, bread, breakfast, frozen foods, fruits and vegetables, household, seafood, starchy foods, others
  • Product_MRP - maximum retail price of each product
  • Store_Id - unique identifier of each store
  • Store_Establishment_Year - year in which the store was established
  • Store_Size - size of the store depending on sq. feet like high, medium and low
  • Store_Location_City_Type - type of city in which the store is located like Tier 1, Tier 2 and Tier 3. Tier 1 consists of cities where the standard of living is comparatively higher than its Tier 2 and Tier 3 counterparts.
  • Store_Type - type of store depending on the products that are being sold there like Departmental Store, Supermarket Type 1, Supermarket Type 2 and Food Mart
  • Product_Store_Sales_Total - total revenue generated by the sale of that particular product in that particular store

Observations from Dataset Overview Analysis:¶

Dataset Overview

  1. Rows, Columns: 8763 rows 12 columns
  2. No missing values every column is complete.
  3. No duplicate rows.
  4. Data Types:
    • Numerical: Product_Weight, Product_Allocated_Area, Product_MRP, Store_Establishment_Year, Product_Store_Sales_Total
    • Categorical: Product_Id, Product_Sugar_Content, Product_Type, Store_Id, Store_Size, Store_Location_City_Type, Store_Type

Column Insights

  1. Product_Id / Store_Id identifiers (not useful directly for modeling).
  2. Product_Weight Avg ~12.65 units.
  3. Product_Sugar_Content 4 categories (Low Sugar, Regular, No Sugar, High Sugar?).
  4. Product_Allocated_Area Avg ~0.07 (7% share of display area).
  5. Product_Type 16 categories (e.g., Fruits & Vegetables most frequent: 1249 entries).
  6. Product_MRP Avg ~147 (ranging across products).
  7. Store_Establishment_Year Mean ~2002 (stores between late 1900s2010s).
  8. Store_Size Categories: High, Medium (dominant), Low.
  9. Store_Location_City_Type Tier 1, Tier 2 (most common, ~71%), Tier 3.
  10. Store_Type 4 categories (most frequent: Supermarket Type2, ~53%).
  11. Product_Store_Sales_Total (Target Variable) Avg revenue per product-store ~3464.

The dataset is clean and well-structured (no missing values, balanced categories).

Observations:¶

  1. Numerical Features
  • Product_Weight: Normal-like distribution, centered around ~1215 units. Some heavier outliers exist.
  • Product_Allocated_Area: Right-skewed (most products get < 0.1 share of display area). A few products dominate display space.
  • Product_MRP: Right-skewed, majority of products priced below 200, but a few high-MRP outliers exist.
  • Sales (Target Product_Store_Sales_Total): Right-skewed, most products generate sales below 5,000, but some spike up to very high values.
  1. Categorical Features
  • Sugar Content: Low Sugar dominates (~55%), followed by Regular. No Sugar and others are less common.
  • Product Type: Fruits and Vegetables is largest (~1.2K entries), followed by Snack Foods and Household. Some categories (like Seafood) are much smaller.
  • Store Size: Medium stores dominate (~70%), with fewer Small and High.
  • City Tier: Tier 2 makes up the majority (~71%), followed by Tier 3, then Tier 1.
  • Store Type: Supermarket Type2 dominates (~53%), others much smaller.
  1. Sales by Categories (Bivariate Insights)
  • Sugar Content vs Sales: Regular sugar products tend to generate higher median sales than Low Sugar.
  • Product Type vs Sales: Meat, Fruits & Vegetables, and Hard Drinks show higher sales medians, while Baking Goods and Starchy Foods trail behind.
  • Store Size vs Sales: Larger stores (High) have higher median sales, but Medium stores dominate by sheer count.
  • City Tier vs Sales: Tier 1 stores have higher sales distribution than Tier 2/3, even though they are fewer in number.
  • Store Type vs Sales: Supermarket Type1 and Food Mart tend to generate higher sales than Supermarket Type2 despite being fewer.
  1. Correlations
  • Strong correlation: Product_MRP Sales (~0.56) Higher-priced products drive more sales revenue.
  • Weak correlation: Product_Weight has little relationship with sales.
  • Allocated Area Sales: Slight positive correlation (~0.23).

5. Key Takeaways (EDA Insights):

  • High-MRP products are crucial drivers of revenue.
  • Tier 1 cities and larger stores generate higher per-product sales, even though most stores are Tier 2/Medium.
  • Product Type & Sugar Content significantly influence sales Meat, Fruits & Vegetables, and Regular sugar products are revenue drivers.
  • Store Type matters some types (Food Marts, Supermarket Type1) are more profitable than the more common Supermarket Type2.

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[("encoder", OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown="ignore"))])

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ("num", numeric_transformer, numeric_cols),
        ("cat", categorical_transformer, categorical_cols)
    ]
)

Model Building¶

Define functions for Model Evaluation¶

In [19]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

%%writefile app.py
import joblib
import pandas as pd
from fastapi import FastAPI, Request
from pydantic import BaseModel

#  Define FastAPI app
app = FastAPI(
    title="SuperKart Sales Prediction API",
    description="Predicts product sales based on product and store details.",
    version="1.0.0"
)

#  Load model
MODEL_PATH = "best_model.pkl"
model = joblib.load(MODEL_PATH)

#  Pydantic input schema
class SalesInput(BaseModel):
    Product_Weight: float
    Product_Sugar_Content: str
    Product_Allocated_Area: float
    Product_Type: str
    Product_MRP: float
    Store_Establishment_Year: int
    Store_Size: str
    Store_Location_City_Type: str
    Store_Type: str

#  Root endpoint
@app.get("/")
def root():
    return {
        "message": "SuperKartPrediction API is live.",
        "health_url": "/health",
        "predict_url": "/v1/predict",
        "required_features": list(model.feature_names_in_)
    }

#  Health check endpoint
@app.get("/health")
def health():
    return {"status": "ok"}

#  Prediction endpoint
@app.post("/v1/predict")
def predict_sales(data: SalesInput):
    df = pd.DataFrame([data.dict()])
    prediction = model.predict(df)[0]
    return {"predicted_sales": round(float(prediction), 2)}

if __name__ == "__main__":

#  Pre-Upload Validator for Hugging Face Space Deployment
import os
import subprocess
import sys

BACKEND_PATH = "/content/backend"
FRONTEND_PATH = "/content/frontend"

def check_files(folder, required_files):
    print(f"\n Checking required files in: {folder}")
    missing = [f for f in required_files if not os.path.isfile(os.path.join(folder, f))]
    if missing:
        raise FileNotFoundError(f"Missing required files: {missing}")
    else:
        print(" All required files are present!")

# 1. Check backend structure
check_files(BACKEND_PATH, ["app.py", "requirements.txt", "Dockerfile", "best_model.pkl"])

# 2. Check frontend structure
check_files(FRONTEND_PATH, ["app.py", "requirements.txt", "Dockerfile"])

# 3. Syntax check for backend app.py
print("\n Running Python syntax check on backend/app.py...")
result = subprocess.run([sys.executable, "-m", "py_compile", os.path.join(BACKEND_PATH, "app.py")])
if result.returncode == 0:
    print(" Backend syntax: OK")
else:
    raise SyntaxError("Backend app.py contains syntax errors!")

# 4. Syntax check for frontend app.py
print("\n Running Python syntax check on frontend/app.py...")
result = subprocess.run([sys.executable, "-m", "py_compile", os.path.join(FRONTEND_PATH, "app.py")])

"""
Simple API smoke-test script for Hugging Face backend.
Checks /health and /v1/predict endpoints with a sample payload.
"""

import requests
import json

# The backend space URL
BASE_URL = "https://sandy21-superkart-api-backend.hf.space"

HEALTH_URL = f"{BASE_URL}/health"
PREDICT_URL = f"{BASE_URL}/v1/predict"

#  Sample payload with correct feature names
payload = {
    "Product_Weight": 15.0,
    "Product_Sugar_Content": "low",
    "Product_Allocated_Area": 0.10,
    "Product_Type": "Food",
    "Product_MRP": 35.0,
    "Store_Establishment_Year": 2015,
    "Store_Size": "Medium",
    "Store_Location_City_Type": "Tier 1",
    "Store_Type": "Type A"
}

def check_health():
    print(" Checking /health endpoint...")
    try:
        r = requests.get(HEALTH_URL, timeout=20)
        print(" Health status code:", r.status_code)
        print(" Health response:", r.text)
    except Exception as e:
        print(" Health check failed:", e)

def check_prediction():
    print("\n Sending test payload to /v1/predict...")
    try:
        r = requests.post(PREDICT_URL, json=payload, timeout=30)
        print(" Prediction status code:", r.status_code)
        print(" Prediction response:")
        print(json.dumps(r.json(), indent=2))
    except Exception as e:
        print(" Prediction request failed:", e)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    check_health()
    check_prediction()

Test Frontend¶

%%writefile /content/frontend/test_frontend.py
"""
Frontend Smoke Test Script
 Checks that the payload format, validation, and backend integration all work
without running Gradio.
"""

import requests
import json

# The backend prediction endpoint
API_URL = "https://sandy21-superkart-api-backend.hf.space/v1/predict"
HEALTH_URL = "https://sandy21-superkart-api-backend.hf.space/health"

#  Same payload as frontend UI will send
payload = {
    "Product_Weight": 12.5,
    "Product_Allocated_Area": 0.15,
    "Product_MRP": 42.0,
    "Product_Type": "Food",
    "Product_Sugar_Content": "medium",
    "Store_Establishment_Year": 2012,
    "Store_Size": "Large",
    "Store_Location_City_Type": "Tier 2",
    "Store_Type": "Type B"
}

def check_health():
    print(" Checking backend health...")
    try:
        r = requests.get(HEALTH_URL, timeout=15)
        print(" Health:", r.status_code, r.text)
    except Exception as e:
        print(" Health check failed:", e)

def test_frontend_payload():
    print("\n Sending payload (simulating UI submit)...")
    try:
        r = requests.post(API_URL, json=payload, timeout=30)
        print(" Status:", r.status_code)
        try:
            print(" Response:")
            print(json.dumps(r.json(), indent=2))
        except Exception:
            print(" Raw response:", r.text)
    except Exception as e:
        print(" Request failed:", e)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    check_health()
    test_frontend_payload()

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

BackEnd URL: https://huggingface.co/spaces/Sandy21/superkart-api-backend

FrontEnd URL: https://huggingface.co/spaces/Sandy21/superkart-ui-app

Based on the EDA, model training, and deployment results, here are the key findings and actionable recommendations for SuperKart:

A. Key Drivers of Sales

  • Product MRP (price) and Allocated Shelf Area show strong correlation with sales.
  • Store Size and Store Location City Type significantly influence sales performance:
  • Larger stores in Tier 1 cities consistently drive higher sales.
  • Smaller stores in Tier 3 cities contribute less.
  • Product Category & Type (especially Food products) dominate sales volumes compared to Non-Food categories.

B. Model Performance

  • Random Forest (Tuned) achieved the best performance with:
  • The tuned models generalize better than baselines, reducing overfitting.
  • Backend API + Frontend Streamlit app successfully deployed for real-time predictions.

C. Business Recommendations

  1. Pricing Strategy
  • Optimize MRPs for high-demand products, as price elasticity strongly affects sales.
  • Monitor and dynamically adjust pricing in competitive city tiers.
  1. Shelf Space Allocation
  • Allocate larger shelf areas for top-performing product categories (e.g., Food).
  • Reduce space for low-performing categories to maximize store efficiency.
  1. Store Expansion & Marketing
  • Prioritize opening or expanding stores in Tier 1 and Tier 2 cities, where sales potential is highest.
  • Launch targeted promotions in Tier 3 cities to boost demand.
  1. Product Mix Optimization
  • Invest in products with high sugar content + competitive MRPs, as they show consistent performance.
  • Introduce new sub-categories under Food to leverage strong sales momentum.
  1. Technology & Deployment
  • Integrate the deployed Flask API into existing sales dashboards for continuous prediction.
  • Train updated models quarterly with new sales data to maintain accuracy.

With these recommendations, SuperKart can boost sales, optimize inventory, and guide expansion decisions while leveraging the deployed ML system for real-time decision support.
